Yea it’s not that 7/11 in SG is bad, personally I just feel like the things in 7/11, although delicious, can be overpriced.

In Singapore it’s easy to go to a hawker center and order freshly cooked food that is of a similar or cheaper price
And since hawker centers or coffee shops are common in the country they’re just as convenient

Probably why locals don’t eat in a 7/11 as often as people from other countries

(Plus who would get chicken rice in 7/11 when u could get it at mrt stations for $2)

snippet.textDisplay:
7-11 is very very very overprice in Singapore unlike Thailand, Taiwan or even Japan which is why many of us would tell you there is nothing there. An instant chicken rice cost $6 when you can get fresh chicken rice at a stall for $2-3, a can of coke cost $3 you can get it for $0.70 outside..

7-11 Singapore is also unpopular with the locals since many of the supermarket are opening 24hrs here and they don't inflate the price, only tourist and people that drink till the late night at town area still go to 7-11 because of the brand not because of their good food.. The only thing I ever eaten from 7-11 is that bryani and that was years ago, it is good but not worth the hype..Sorry.

snippet.textDisplay:
Not to be mean but... you should've drained that ramen before you actually ate it😅. Mi goreng stands for fried noodles. And we have the same product here in Malaysia. And it's kinda written on the guide on how to make it.
I'm not saying you can't have it that way, it's just that I once accidentally turned it into a noodle soup as I forgot to drain it and I kinda think it tasted horrible. If you really want the original full and better experience, drain the water before adding the spice. Because all the packets in there are to be used to make the noodle sauce not soup.😅
(It's like a samyang korean spicy noodles)

Not to be mean but... you should've drained that ramen before you actually ate it😅. Mi goreng stands for fried noodles. And we have the same product here in Malaysia. And it's kinda written on the guide on how to make it.
I'm not saying you can't have it that way, it's just that I once accidentally turned it into a noodle soup as I forgot to drain it and I kinda think it tasted horrible. If you really want the original full and better experience, drain the water before adding the spice. Because all the packets in there are to be used to make the noodle sauce not soup.😅
(It's like a samyang korean spicy noodles)
